An Analysis of Pollution and Algae in the Chesapeake Bay

By Nick LaRossa, John Skipper, Dylan Celli¶

Introduction¶

The subject of this tutorial is analyzing the trends of pollution levels in the Chesapeake Bay from the year 2000 to 2020.

The goal of this tutorial is to determine if Maryland will reach the pollution goals set for itself by the year 2025 and what that will mean for the Chesapeake Bay. Over the course of this project we will show the relationship between pollution levels, HABs, cleanup efforts, and water quality.

Motive¶

To someone who goes to the Chesapeake Bay in person today, they may think that at best there is nothing wrong with the water and at worst they may believe that the only issue plaguing it is human made trash like plastics. While that certainly contributes to the overall pollution, the fact is that things we cannot see are just as bad. Algal blooms create what is called “dead zones,” which results in massive consumption of the oxygen in the water by bacteria. Not only is this bad for humans who wish to swim in the bay, but also for lifeforms who live in it. For instance, fish who are forced to swim in a location with a lack of oxygen are at risk of mass death.

What, exactly, can we plan to do about this, and how can Data Science help us to achieve that result? We set out to find out what can most effect the restoring the Bay, which is the focal point of this project. In addition, we will look at if current methods of pollution control are effective, what needs to be done to make them more effective (if anything) and what the future looks like if we continue with current trends.

Using data science we have gathered plenty of data on the health of the Bay. What makes data science so useful for this project is that it allowed us to comb through so many years of information and conversation in order to find out what is really impacting the bay. As you view our page, take a look at all of the visualizations we have created, which will hopefully indicate to you why exactly it is important to look at the things we cannot necessarily see.

Something that is very interesting that we have learned through this project is the manipulation of data for other people’s own goals. For instance, a graph may show that data of nitrogen pollution has gone up and down and up and down across a few years, however, a company invested in “removing” nitrogen may cherry pick the data and only select the points at the local minimums, completely removing any information to be gained from what is really happening. This can be very lucrative, as it can encourage others to invest in one group over another simply due to the investors or helpers being misled by false data.

We hope that at the very least we can convince you that the health of the Chesapeake Bay is in needed of our assistance.

Part 1: Exploratory Analysis for Nutrient Pollution in the Bay

Our pollution analysis will focus on nutrient pollution. Nutrient pollution consists of three main components: Nitrogen, Phosphorus, and soil. Human derived nutrient pollution has been an affliction in the Chesapeake Bay for over fifty years. During the 1970s pollution hit a critical point as the aquatic life in the bay started to disappear. Due to the decline in aquatic life, efforts were started to determine the causes and solutions to the decline in the quality of the Chesapeake Bay waters. The EPA completed a five-year study and determined that nutrient pollution was the cause of the decline in the quality of the bay.

def sub_list(original, search): #takes a list and returns elements from the list that contain the search parameter
    return [i for i in original if search in i]

def unwanted_list(full,wanted): # Sets: all bodies - desired bodies = unwanted bodies
    return list(set(full)-set(wanted))

def scale_col(column):#normalizes the values of the column passed in
    return (column - column.mean()) / column.std()

def ave_lin_reg_plot(frame, labels, title):#used for west vs east bay plots as they were repetative
    ave_frame =  frame.groupby(['Major Basin','Year']).mean().reset_index()
    basins = ave_frame['Major Basin'].unique()
    for basin in basins:
        data = ave_frame[ave_frame['Major Basin'] == basin]
        X = data.Year[1:-2].astype(int)
        y = data["Total lbs."][1:-2]
        sns.regplot(x=X, y=y)
    plt.legend(labels=labels, loc = 2, bbox_to_anchor = (1,1))
    plt.title(title)
    
def pollution_cleaning(filename):
    df = pd.read_csv(filename)
    df.drop(['Land-River Segment', 'FIPS'], axis=1, inplace=True)

    temp_dict = {}
    for column in df.columns[4:]:
        temp_dict[column] = re.findall("\d{4}", column)[0]

    df.rename(columns=temp_dict, inplace = True)
    df = pd.melt(df,id_vars=['County','Tributary Basin','Major Basin','Source Sector'], \
                          var_name='Year', value_name='Total lbs.')

    unwanted = sub_list(df['Major Basin'].unique() ,"Basin")
    df = df.set_index("Major Basin")
    df.drop(unwanted,axis=0,inplace=True)
    df = df.reset_index()

    wanted = sub_list(df['Tributary Basin'].unique(),"Shore")
    all_bodies = df['Tributary Basin'].unique()
    df = df.set_index("Tributary Basin")
    df.drop( unwanted_list( all_bodies, wanted) , axis=0, inplace=True)
    df = df.reset_index()
    
    return df

We scrapped the data for these pollutants from the Maryland Open Data Portal, a website created by the Maryland government that provides publicly accessible datasets. Due to the nature of the data that we analyze it cannot reveal a complete depiction of pollution. This is because there are two general categories of pollution sources: point and nonpoint pollution. The MD Department of the Environment denotes point pollution as “originates from a single, easily identifiable source, and is the form of pollution with which most people are familiar.” Non-point pollution is denoted as “comes from a broad area where it is not possible to readily identify a single source of contamination.”

To clean the initial pollution datasets we had to

  • Remove irrelevant bodies of water using the pandas drop feature
  • We determined that the bodies were irrelevant if they did not connect directly with the Cheasapeake Bay
  • Reformat the columns of the year for observations to graph the data later
    • EX: Total N, 1985 (lb.) → 1985
  • Use the pandas melt feature to convert the dataset from wide to long
    • Before
      • County
      • Tributary Basin
      • Major Basin
      • Source Sector
      • Total N, 1985 (lb.) … Total N, 2016(lb.)
    • After
      • County
      • Tributary Basin
      • Major Basin
      • Source Sector
      • Year
      • Total lbs.

After we cleaned the data we created visualizations for the trends of the data. For the pollution data we used the python library Seaborn. To learn about the basics of Seaborn, we highly suggest reading this article. The trends that Seaborn’s regplot feature created shows that the nutrients pollution data could easily be estimated with a simple linear regression. The simplicity of the regression can most likely be attributed to people because pollution is created and controlled by people, which means that there are most likely guidelines and goals that are being followed.

After creating the visualization for the nutrient pollution it was apparent that location was another factor affecting the data. After removing the unnecessary major basins the only basins left in the dataset were the Western and Eastern Chesapeake Bay. The graph creates a fantastic visual representation of the differences between the two locations in the bay. To make the different bays more apparent we made them different colors with the matplotlib legend feature. It appears that the linear regression for the Western bay is expected to be ten times greater than the regression for the Eastern bay.

It is important to note that the plots below show an average for the pollution across all source sectors for a given year. We figured the average pollution across all source sectors would give us a good first look at the data. It gives us a representation of how much pollution will be contained in each reported land-river segment for a year and what we should really expect to see.

The nitrogen dataset was originally segmented off into samples from the different Land-River Segments that exist in the Major Basins we chose. We decided to sum up the totals and look at them completely to see how all of them combine to make the overall amount of Nitrogen Pollution in the Bay. We first group by Year and sum across all of the source sectors to get the total amount of pounds of pollution in the bay each year. This can be seen below. We then use SKlearn's linear regression model to find a line of best fit through these data points. This might be a better way to see than the averages and it is better to use when trying to follow chesapeake's future 2025 standards.

In [8]:
nitrogen_df = nitrogen_df[nitrogen_df['Year'] != '1985']
nitrogen_df = nitrogen_df[nitrogen_df['Year'] != '2025']
nitrogen_df = nitrogen_df[nitrogen_df['Year'] != '2017']
nitrogen_df['Year'] = pd.to_numeric(nitrogen_df['Year'])
phosphorus_df['Year'] = pd.to_numeric(phosphorus_df['Year'])

phosphorus_df = phosphorus_df[phosphorus_df['Year'] != '1985']
phosphorus_df = phosphorus_df[phosphorus_df['Year'] != '2025']
phosphorus_df = phosphorus_df[phosphorus_df['Year'] != '2017']

sumyear_N_df = nitrogen_df.groupby(by = 'Year').sum().reset_index()
sumyear_N_df = sumyear_N_df.dropna()
fig = plt.figure(figsize = (7, 7))
plt.scatter(sumyear_N_df['Year'], sumyear_N_df['Total lbs.'])
N_model = LinearRegression()
N_model = N_model.fit(np.array(sumyear_N_df['Year']).reshape(-1, 1), sumyear_N_df['Total lbs.'])
plt.plot(sumyear_N_df['Year'], N_model.coef_ * sumyear_N_df['Year'].astype(float) + N_model.intercept_)
N_predicted = N_model.coef_ * sumyear_N_df['Year'].astype(float) + N_model.intercept_
r2 = r2_score(sumyear_N_df['Total lbs.'], N_predicted)
print("The r^2 score for this regression line is " + str(r2))
plt.ylabel('Total pounds of Nitrogen Across All Land-River Segments')
plt.xlabel('Year')
plt.title('Total pounds of Nitrogen over Time')

The r^2 score for this regression line is 0.8254678606574919
Out[8]:
Text(0.5, 1.0, 'Total pounds of Nitrogen over Time')

From the above graph, it is obvious to see that Nitrogen pollution is trending downwards from 2007-2016. The linear regression model reflects that and we even got an r^2 score of 0.8254 which means that the data is going down over time. This does not present the idea that time is a factor, but there are other changes that are happening that are causing the pollution to go down over time such as efforts to cleanup the bay, more restrictions on polluting, and others that we explore a bit later in this project. We could use this model to predict what the total amount of pollution will be in 2025 to get an estimate of will the Chesapeake Bay authority reach it's intended nutrient pollution goals of 2025.

An estimate into Goal Meeting

The Chesapeake Progress pollution goals are looking to achieve a 75% overall reduction of nitrogen and phosphorus pollution by 2025. Before we started, this seemed to be pretty ambitious as curving pollution that quickly seems to be very hard given the state of the plastics and other industries today. After grabbing our datasets we were more inclined to figure out if they even have a shot at completing this. From the website, this plan was enacted to start in 2009 and reach its end goal by 2025, so that's a span of 16 years for the Bay cleanup to reach its goal.

Below we have a look at that using the models generated previously that had pollution correlated with year.

N_2025 = ((N_model.coef_ * 2025) + N_model.intercept_)[0]
N_2009 = (sumyear_N_df[sumyear_N_df['Year'] == 2009]).iloc[0, 1]
dif = N_2009 - N_2025
N_decr = (dif / N_2009) * 100
print('The percentage Nitrogen Pollution decrease from 2009 to 2025 is predicted to be ' + str(N_decr) + '%.')

P_2025 = ((P_model.coef_ * 2025) + N_model.intercept_)[0]
P_2009 = (sumyear_P_df[sumyear_P_df['Year'] == 2009]).iloc[0, 1]
dif = P_2009 - P_2025
P_decr = (dif / P_2009) * 100
print('The percentage Phosphorus Pollution decrease from 2009 to 2025 is predicted to be ' + str(P_decr) + '%.')

The percentage Nitrogen Pollution decrease from 2009 to 2025 is predicted to be 94.45507988632993%.
The percentage Phosphorus Pollution decrease from 2009 to 2025 is predicted to be 23.57295343779144%.

Based on our models for these two forms of nutrient pollution, we found that the nitrogen pollution is well on it's way to reach its target decrease percentage by 2025. Actually, it even surpasses the goal point by 20% which is wild. This could be due to a number of factors such that there were outliers in the early years of 2007 that skewed the total amount of pollution such that it was easier to reach the target. The model itself could not really be representative as we are correlating years to nitrogen pollution concentration. It might have been better if we had used some different kind of source to create the model. It could also be that the bay is being cleaned up well and that they are potentially meeting their targets based on the dataset we used. A lot of factors could be attributed here to this outcome.

With respect to the phosphorus data, it seems to be more realistic as the expected decrease in phosphorus pollution from 2009 to 2025 is expected to be 34%. This seems way more on line with what we expected, as attempts to solidify pollution reduction efforts in the past have seem to be relatively unstable. Still, a 34% decrease in phosphorus pollution is still a good prediction nonetheless because any decrease in nutrient pollution in the bay is better than none at all. We are happy our model still shows a negative trend for both points of nutrient pollution and consider the current bay efforts a success based on the dataset we used in this tutorial

To clean the Living resources (microorganisms) datasets I had to

  • Remove unnecessary columns (pandas drop)
    • ReportingUnit
    • Parameter
    • SampleType
    • SampleNumber
    • TSN
    • NODCCode
    • SPECCode
  • Remove unnecessary observations (removed rows using pandas drop)
    • We created a set of the microorganisms that I wanted and removed them from a set of all the microorganisms
    • After we removed all the microorganisms that were unwanted
  • Reformat the sample date to just be years
    • Keep only the year from the sample date to simplify linear regression

The microorganism and dissolved oxygen data followed a non linear trend over the time; a polynomial linear regression of the fourth power provided the best fit for the data. A polynomial linear regression provided a better fit for the data due to the numerous variables that impact dissolved oxygen levels and microorganism growth.

for name in algae_df.LatinName.unique():
    fig, ax = plt.subplots()
    temp = algae_df[algae_df['LatinName'] == name]
    temp = temp.groupby('Year').mean().reset_index()
    z = temp['ReportingValue(L)'].max() + 10000
    plt.ylim(ymin = -1000, ymax = z)
    ax = sns.regplot(data = temp, order=2, x='Year', y='ReportingValue(L)',truncate = True)
    title = "Annual Average of "+name
    ax.set_title(title)

All of the linear regressions have one common event, in between the years 2010 and 2012 there is a sharp change in the slope of the data. For the pollution data there is a rapid decline. For the microorganisms there is a rapid increase between the years 2010 and 2011 and a subsequent rapid decrease in population. The cleanup data demonstrates the most dramatic changes between 2010 and 2011. The clean up activities that best displays this jump are the treatment plant retrofits and the cover crops planted. These trends suggest that there exists a relationship between pollution reduction efforts, bay pollutants, and the microorganism population. The reason for these drastic changes in the data is most likely due to the sudden boom in microorganism population and the resulting decision by the EPA to institute a new clean up effort.

    #to remove NaN values in the list without removing from the dataframe

    y = [i for i in activites_df[activity] if pd.notna(i)]

    polynomial_features= PolynomialFeatures(degree=2)

    model = LinearRegression()
    model.fit(x_poly, y)
    y_poly_pred = model.predict(x_poly)

    model = LinearRegression()
    model.fit(x_poly, y)
    y_poly_pred = model.predict(x_poly)
    plt.scatter(x, y)
    plt.plot(x, y_poly_pred)

The significance of the disolved oxygen levels in the bay is that it is a considered a good general indicator of the health of anybody of water. Most aquatic organisms require oxygen to survive, which means that when the fall too low they will die, this is known as hypoxia. Due to the limited resources of this tutorial we cannot explain every aspect of the data trends. There are dozens of variables that can influence the amount of algae or oxygen in the bay. One example of the variables that affect the health of the bay is rainfall. We created a line plot of the averages for the average annual rainfall and nitrogen pollution. To create the line plot we had to normalize the data so that the data worked on the same scale. We normalized the data by taking every value in the columns and subtracting the mean column value and then dividing by the column’s standard deviation. While the relationship between the two is not strong (a correlation coefficient of about 62%) it is clear that in the years that have more precipitation there is a spike in nitrogen pollution. When we researched the topic we realized that this is more than correlation, it is causation. According to the EPA, the runoff water from rainfall picks up the pollutants in the ground as it finds its way into the nearest body of water. Polluted runoff means that as rainfall increases there is more runoff ending up in the Chesapeake Bay causing a spike in annual pollution. Another factor that impacts our data is geographic bias. Due to real life limitations it is impossible to get a highly accurate depiction of the bay as a whole. Not all parts of the bay are the same and some parts are cleaner than others, which can bias data averages.

There are dozens of variables that impact the level of pollutants and the overall health of the bay, which extrapolates a linear regression for the data most likely incorrect. An example of the limitations of my simple linear regression is that it will eventually become negative, which is impossible for pollution loads.
The damage done by the HAB is not limited to the nutrients they consume or the toxins that they emit; they wreck the most havoc after they die. After billions of different algae die they start to decompose which is where bacteria come into the picture. Bacteria are needed to break down the billions of dead microorganisms in the water everyday. When bacteria decompose the algae, the bacteria use up oxygen in the water. Normally, bacteria breaking down dead material has no impact on the ecosystem, however, when there are billions of algae for the bacteria to decompose this destroys the oxygen in the water. This is what has happened to the Chesapeake Bay over the past few decades. As the nutrient pollution increased the amount of algae increased which led to more dead algae for bacteria to decompose. As the bacteria decompose the vast quantities they use up too much of the oxygen in the water which creates dead zones. As the bacteria take more oxygen out of the water it will be more hazardous to other aquatic life; eventually it will be deadly to them. The EPA states that the amount of dissolved oxygen in the water is a good indicator of the life that those waters can support. If you want to learn more about the lethal levels of hypoxia, the lack of oxygen in the water, look at this four page article by the Ecological Society of America. The improving dissolved oxygen levels demonstrate that the decades clean up have been effective. Over time the oxygen levels have improved slowly which shows promise that the bay will become more hospitable to aquatic life.

Part 4: Cross Referencing Datasets

Throughout this tutorial, we've talked about multiple forms of pollution, algae, oxygen concentrations and more. A more interesting take at the end of all of this is to see if we can cross reference datasets to try and find out if they correlate well. It is well documented that higher amounts of nutrient pollution can lead to higher concentrations of harmful algal blooms. Below we tried to cross reference these datasets and see if we could find ourselves a meaningful correlation that we expect based on prior knowledge. We used the total reporting value in Liters of the algae prorocentrum minimum and the total pounds of nitrogen and phosphorus pollution respectively in two different graphs with two different models.

In [34]:
PM = algae_df[algae_df['LatinName'] == 'Prorocentrum minimum']
PM = PM.groupby('Year').sum().reset_index()
sum_N = nitrogen_df.groupby('Year').sum().reset_index()
N_joined = sum_N.merge(PM, how = 'inner')

fig = plt.figure(figsize = (7, 7))
plt.scatter(N_joined['Total lbs.'], N_joined['ReportingValue(L)'])
cross_model = LinearRegression()
cross_model = cross_model.fit(np.array(N_joined['Total lbs.']).reshape(-1, 1), N_joined['ReportingValue(L)'])
plt.plot(N_joined['Total lbs.'], cross_model.coef_ * N_joined['Total lbs.'] + cross_model.intercept_)
NPM_predicted = cross_model.coef_ * N_joined['Total lbs.'] + cross_model.intercept_
r2 = r2_score(N_joined['ReportingValue(L)'], NPM_predicted)
print('The r^2 score for this regression line is ' + str(r2))
plt.xlabel('Total lbs. of Nitrogen Pollution for a year.')
plt.ylabel('Total reporting value in Liters for a year')
plt.title('Total lbs. of N vs. Prorocentrum Minimum Concentration')

The r^2 score for this regression line is 0.4252033541130129
Out[34]:
Text(0.5, 1.0, 'Total lbs. of N vs. Prorocentrum Minimum Concentration')

As can be seen above, the linear regression is ok at representing the correlation, but it seems that the correlation is not really that strong at all. We got an r^2 score of 0.4252. However, this is better than we expected because we were crossing values from different datasets and we did not expect this to workout that well in the first place. It seems that this is sort of a success but not an astounding one by any means.

Insight and Policy Decision¶

One way in which the pollution can be prevented from entering the bay is by finding new ways of cleaning runoff water. As the the line plots displayed as rain increases there will be more pollution in the bay. If the issue of polluted runoff water can be solved it may significantly decrease the amount of pollution that eneters the bay every year.

Another main source of pollution that we found was that the majority of nitrogen and phosphorus pollution comes from river input into bay. Pollution of runoff water contributes to the river's total, but wastewater and marine dumping also contributes to this same source. Based on a second nitrogen dataset we found directly above this, it seems that the majority of pollution comes from the river input while both wasterwater and non-point downstream sites also contribute to the Chesapeake Bay's pollution.

The best course of policy action is to attack the individual sources of point pollution that contribute to the input of pollution in the rivers as the rivers generally are the cause for much of the pollution in the bay. This can be dealt with by limiting fertilizer usage in agriculture, preventing sewage leaks, reducing oil spills, and many other ways. Each respective field should be focused on limiting their own pollution as much as possible as they all contribute to the rivers and therefore the pollution of the bay.

Conclusion¶

Our exploratory analysis of pollution, algae, and oxygen levels demonstrate that the actions that people have taken to clean the bay over the past few decades have been effective. However, the data also shows that even the best cleanup efforts can be nullified by elements outside human control. Based on our predictive models, we are hoping that the pollution follows the course of the model and hits the 75% reduction by 2025, although there is no guarantee that may happen as cleanup efforts could change as COVID changes, or pollution could increase again if restrictions are lightened up in response to the known/predicted decrease in nutrient pollution. We also hope to see an overall reduciton in harmful algal blooms as shown in our tutorial because harmful algal blooms may release cyanotoxins and lead to things like shellfish poisoning. Although we did not predict whether that would change, the population seems rather steady so i assume that the algae concentration will remain intact for the most part. Lastly, we have shown that there are many things that influence the health of the bay besides what we have shown here, and that everything must be done to keep it in good health for the sea life that live in it as well as us humans who thrive off of it.

We hope you enjoyed our tutorial! Thanks for reading.
